---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import LayerSection from '../components/LayerSection.astro';
import { siliconLayers } from '../data/siliconLayers.js';
import Doping from '../components/Doping.svelte';
import Diode from '../components/Diode.svelte';
import Mosfet from '../components/Mosfet.svelte';
import CmosInverter from '../components/CmosInverter.svelte';
import Why from '../components/Why.astro';
import Takeaway from '../components/Takeaway.astro';
import Quiz from '../components/Quiz.svelte';
import PrevNext from '../components/PrevNext.astro';
const L = Object.fromEntries(siliconLayers.map((l) => [l.id, l]));
const title = 'THE STACK — silicon';
const description = 'A deep dive into the physics under the stack: doping, the PN-junction diode, the MOSFET as a voltage-controlled switch, and how two switches make a CMOS gate.';
---
<Base {title} {description} layers={siliconLayers}>
  <div slot="hero">
    <div class="kicker">A deep dive into layer −01</div>
    <h1 class="title">THE <em>SILICON</em><br />STACK</h1>
    <p class="lede">Every abstraction in the stack rests on one physical miracle: a rock we taught to switch. This is the bottom of the bottom — how a purified crystal, salted with the right impurities, becomes a valve, then a switch, then the logic gate everything else is built from.</p>
    <div class="hero-meta"><a class="back-link" href="/">← back to the full stack</a> · crystal → doping → junction → MOSFET → logic gate</div>
  </div>

  <LayerSection {...L.SI0}>
    <p class="prose">Silicon sits in the periodic table's sweet spot: four outer electrons, every one locked into a bond with a neighbour in a tidy crystal. With no charge free to move, pure silicon is a <span class="hl">semiconductor</span> — not quite a conductor, not quite an insulator. That "almost" is the whole opportunity.</p>
    <Takeaway>Pure silicon barely conducts — and being right on the edge is exactly what lets a tiny change flip it between blocking and passing current.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="To build a switch we need a material we can push between two states — conducting and not — reliably, billions of times, in a space too small to see."
      idea="Use a semiconductor: a crystal whose conductivity sits on a knife’s edge, so a small, controllable nudge tips it one way or the other."
      tradeoff="Pure silicon on its own does nothing useful — it needs to be deliberately, precisely contaminated to become controllable."
      next="That deliberate contamination is called doping."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.SI1}>
    <p class="prose">Mix in a trace of another element and the crystal gains carriers. <b>Phosphorus</b> (five outer electrons) leaves a spare electron free to roam — <span class="hl">n-type</span>. <b>Boron</b> (three) leaves a missing bond, a <span class="hl">hole</span> that drifts like a positive charge — <span class="hl">p-type</span>.</p>
    <Doping client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Doping turns inert silicon into a conductor on demand: donors add free electrons (n-type), acceptors add holes (p-type).</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="A semiconductor on the edge is useless until we can decide which way it leans — and add charge carriers we control."
      idea="Substitute a few atoms with ones that have one more or one fewer outer electron, seeding the crystal with free electrons or holes."
      tradeoff="The doping must be astonishingly pure and precise — stray contamination ruins the carefully tuned carrier balance."
      next="The magic appears when you put a p-type region right next to an n-type one."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.SI2}>
    <p class="prose">Join p-type and n-type material and something remarkable happens at the seam: electrons fill nearby holes, leaving a carrier-free <span class="hl">depletion region</span> that blocks current. Push from one side and it collapses (current flows); push from the other and it widens (blocked). A <b>one-way valve</b>.</p>
    <Diode client:visible />
    <Takeaway>A PN junction conducts in only one direction — the first real device, the diode, built purely from where two doped regions meet.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Carriers alone don’t compute; we need a structure whose conduction we can steer with an applied voltage."
      idea="Abut p-type and n-type silicon so a depletion region forms, giving a junction that passes current one way and blocks the other."
      tradeoff="A diode is one-way but uncontrollable mid-stream — it has no separate ‘control’ input, so it can’t yet act as a switch."
      next="Add a third terminal to control the channel and the valve becomes a switch."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.SI3}>
    <p class="prose">A <b>MOSFET</b> adds a control terminal: a metal <span class="hl">gate</span> sitting over an insulator above the silicon. Raise the gate voltage past a threshold and it pulls a conducting <b>channel</b> into existence between source and drain. One voltage decides whether another can flow — a switch with no moving parts.</p>
    <Mosfet client:visible />
    <Takeaway>The MOSFET is the payoff: a voltage on an isolated gate conjures or removes a channel, making a fast, tiny, electrically-controlled switch.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="A diode conducts one way but can’t be turned on and off by a separate signal — computation needs a controllable switch."
      idea="Float a gate above the channel on a thin insulator; its voltage attracts carriers to form (or starve) a channel, switching current without touching it."
      tradeoff="The insulator and channel are only nanometres thick, so leakage, heat, and quantum effects all fight you as the devices shrink."
      next="One switch is binary. Pair two of them and you get a decision: a logic gate."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.SI4}>
    <p class="prose">Stack a p-type FET (which pulls the output up to HIGH) above an n-type FET (which pulls it down to LOW), tie their gates together, and you have a <b>CMOS inverter</b>: exactly one transistor conducts, so the output is always the <i>opposite</i> of the input. That's a <span class="hl">NOT</span> gate — and it sips almost no power while idle.</p>
    <CmosInverter client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Two complementary switches make a logic gate: the CMOS inverter is the bridge from silicon physics to Boolean logic — and the reason chips can pack billions of gates without melting.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="A lone transistor switches current, but logic needs gates that compute clean, restored HIGH/LOW outputs without wasting power."
      idea="Pair a pull-up (p-type) and pull-down (n-type) transistor so one is always off; the output is driven firmly to a rail and almost no current flows straight through."
      tradeoff="Every gate still costs switching energy and a sliver of delay, so billions of them together make heat and timing the central engineering battle."
      next="Zoom back out: this inverter is the first rung the main stack stands on — the logic-gate layer, made real."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <Quiz slug="silicon" client:visible />
  <PrevNext slug="silicon" />
</Base>

<style>
  .back-link{color:var(--accent,var(--signal))}
</style>
